One of the most hard pressed issues in today’s political climate is our economy.  America is always seen as the embodiment of capitalism and economic mobility amongst its citizens.  This would be what the collective consciousness deems, however given the sheer size of our population, the intricacies/bureaucracy of our government and the disparity between classes it is not always the key to freedom as we envision it.  Economic success does not always equate to satisfaction.
Both of the readings addressed how long ago, there was a connection between producers and consumers, giving people a sense of purpose through their work.  Today the worker is often so far removed from the end product of their labor that their work becomes nothing more than a way to earn a check.  Turning life into a repetitive and monoughtenous cycle.
I believe that the working environment today cannot be compared to what it was when labor was not estranged.  Given our large population and the overwhelming demand which it creates, systems need to be streamlined.  A trade off between efficiency and satisfaction.  However in certain industries, craftsmanship is valued over efficiency.  Looking at trades such as woodworking, brewing, glass blowing etc, and hand made products is much more desirable than one made on an assembly line.  These also just happen to be the places where workers tend to be the happiest and I don’t think that that is a coincidence.

Commodity Fetishization and Social Classification
	In a world fueled by consumerism and marketing tactics that influence where the working class allocates their money towards, there is a large aspect of how different products are marketed to the different social classes. Commodity fetishization is a Marxist idea that differentiates the value of a product from the labor that went into creating that product. This idea is highlighted in many capitalistic market structures where the idea of what a product is worth comes from the status of possessing that product. This idea aligns strongly with the social classification of members in a capitalistic society. Social classification is the make up of how a group is organized and looked upon from the perspective of education, race, wealth, and many other factors. In this paper, the descriptions of social classification and commodity fetishization will be focused on the structures within the United States.
	Moreover, as human actions have progressed from fulfilling basic needs like food, water, shelter, and community we have created many false values around products that do not directly have value associated with them from a physical view. This idea of value is pushed upon the working class from the power elites through the processes of marketing and brand recognition. This practice has only furthered the wealth disparity between the power elites and the working class by creating the idea that the working class so align their thoughts of value with the illusory value that the power elite created around these products. With this the working class continues to spend their money on products with little to no functional value while lining the pockets of the power elite who own the means of production of these products. 
	Continuing on, the example of Apple products is a great representation of the practices of the working class playing into the game of the power elites. Apple operates on a very short product life cycle process where an updated product to an existing device is released every year to a year and a half. The product that was released a year ago will have the majority of the functions as the new product but by successful marketing and commodity fetishization people still purchase the new product. This is also led on by third-party companies like tele-service providers who advertise and encourage customers to lease devices then trade them in for the next new model. This practice allows the power elite to control how working class consumers spend their money to further the elites gain. 
	In addition, the practice furthers the wealth disparity between the power elites and working class by making the working class continuously spending money on products that in turn do not have a larger value than the ones before. If the working class continues to spend their money on frivolous items then they do not have the opportunity to invest in practices that will raise their income and generational wealth. By controlling how the working class spends their money then the power elites are able to keep a stable lifestyle and not worry about change. If the wealth distribution changes and shifts to a healthier middle class society then the power elites will not be able to sit comfortably on the throne they have built.
	In conclusion, commodity fetishization will always be used as a method of controlling the working class in turn adding to the pockets of the power elites. The idea of the value of a product does not come from it’s functional activities but the value assigned to it through marketing and the ideas that the power elite want the working class to think of it as.

Nationalism is an interesting social trait of human beings.  While tribalism and group loyalty are inherent to social creatures it is completely unnatural to feel loyalty to a large group outside of a small social group whether that be a village, family or a social circle.  It would seem that the sense of nationalism is an effect of the collective consciousness among those who reside in that country.  This would explain why it occurs despite being an inorganic part of the human psyche.
In microfoundations we explore the origins of humanity’s collective consciousness and it is concluded that the main factor behind this collective thinking is the development of language.  This is something that I find interesting when considering nationalism because languages are one of the largest barriers between cultures and it would seem that this is not coincidental when searching for the source of nationalism.  Of course with a shared language and shared geographic location comes a shared culture to include things such as religion, morals, codes and social/political hierarchies, essentially, the collective consciousness that is associated with that nationality.  
This occurs to the point where this nationality becomes intertwined with a person’s “self” as a result of it being reinforced by the collective consciousness.  A shared language and culture makes it easier to associate and identify with members of the same country.  It would appear that nationalism is really just the tribalism we saw in early homosapiens just on a large scale as a result of growing civilizations.

How Genetics Effect Your Personality
Does nature verses nurture really make a difference? Can individuals be completely different even though they had the same childhood? Although it may seem like a bunch of madness, the answer is yes. Individual’s environments are not the only thing that shape them to be who they are, it is also a matter of genetics. Genetics greatly impact individuals’ social aspects and how they cope with the different environments they are in. The argument of nature versus nurture is a very interesting and important topic and it has a lot of evidence holding it to be true. 
I have seen a great and clear example of this throughout my life. My dad and his brother are both adopted and come from different families, meaning they have completely different genetics. My dad is a couple years younger than his brother, but they were pretty close growing up. My dad did not have the best childhood, as his adoptive mother died when he was nine and she was the one who wanted to adopt my dad and his brother in the first place. Because of this my dad and his brother were left with just their dad (my grandpa) raising them as well as my dad’s oldest sister who stepped in when she could. My grandpa was not the kindest to my dad and his brother and would often tell them how he never wanted them, how useless they were and how he did not love them, and no one ever would. This had a great impact on the development of my dad and his brother’s personalities and social ques, and they struggled because of it. Both my dad and his brother would act out and do things they should not be when their sister was not around to take care of them. Although my dad acted out, he was still a good student and played many sports to help him have an outlet for his bad home life. This is the point where you could start to see a difference between my dad and his brother and how their genetics (nature) made them cope with their environment (nurture) in different ways. 
My dad got good grades in high school and was great at track. On the other hand, my dad’s brother (my uncle) started using drugs and getting into trouble with the law. My uncle was in and out of jail while my dad was in high school, and he continued to be while my dad was in college. My dad had decided that after high school, he wanted to go to college and try to be as successful as he could be. He wanted to attend North Carolina State University, as that is where all his older siblings attended college. This, however, was not in the cards for my dad because he had gotten a scholarship to run track at Western Carolina University and his dad forced him to go there. At Western, my dad struggled with doing his work during his first semester as he had had no structure in his life before then, but after his first semester he got his head in gear and was very successful in college. He joined a fraternity and made lots of friends and got a very good job out of college. All the while, my uncle was still in and out of jail for many different things. After college, my dad began to work at his job and continued to get promoted and transferred to an even bigger company where he could make more money. He is still at this company today, and he is very successful in supporting my family and plans to continue this. Soon after my dad graduated, my uncle began committing major crimes and was put in jail for 25 years. He just got out a couple months ago and is still trying to work on being a functioning member of society, with the help of my dad and his sister. 
My dad and uncles story relates back to nature verses nurture in a couple ways. The concept of nature verses nurture is a long-standing debate about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate: genetics and environment. Genetics being the nature aspect and environment being the nurture aspect. Individuals develop inherited characteristics through their genetics that come out in the right environment. For example, in my dad and uncle’s case, their different inherited characteristics were brought out by their poor childhood environment. My dad took his pent-up sadness and anger and turned it into motivation to be successful, whereas my uncle took these factors and turned to drugs and committing crimes. 
Another example of these social differences between my dad and his brother includes their relationships within their family. My dad resented his father, but never meant any ill intention towards him. My dad made a life for himself and wanted to prove to his dad that he could be successful and loved since he had heard otherwise his whole life. This mentality differs from my uncles because when he had nothing left after turning to the streets, he decided to steal from my grandpa’s business and cut off communications with many people in his family. Even after being in and out of jail all his life, giving him plenty of time to think about how he really wanted to turn his life around, as soon as he got out of the structured prison life he had, he turned back to drugs and crimes almost immediately. 
Finally, my dad and uncle’s situation exhibited a clear example of nature versus nurture in the fact that nothing has changed as my dad and uncle have grown up. Even after spending many, many years in prison, having lots of time to change his mind set about how he wanted his life to be once he got out of prison, he was not able to make this mental change. This really solidified for me that it really is a matter of nature versus nurture going on with my dad and his brother. My uncle could not change his ways, even with the help of my dad and his sister and their level headedness. My dad and his sister tried their hardest to motivate him to be better. Even with the most convincing arguments, my uncle reverted to his original ways because of how his brain is wired, his genetics would not allow him to cope with his childhood environment like my dad’s genetics allowed him to. This is important to the argument because even over time, my uncle never  and his genetics took over.
I never really knew much about my uncle growing up and even the things I did know I did not really think anything of because I was so young. As I started getting older and learning more things about my uncle as well as him and my dad’s childhood, I began to question how their lives ended up so different despite having the same childhood. Everything started to make sense as I learned more and more about my dad and uncle’s childhoods as well as what nature versus nurture entails.

	Overtime various social norms have formed and taken a hold of individuals lives. Society has built up individual’s collective conscious and made them believe that some individuals are superior to others. We have a voice in the back of our heads that constantly tells us that we are better than everybody us. We have been raised in a world where this is normal to think. Society has formed concepts about what is considered to be normal and we feel like we have to live up to them and strictly follow them
	Yuval Noah Harari goes into depth about concept of humility and how society needs to be reminded that we are not the center of the world. In his book, 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, Harari states, “most people tend to believe they are the center of the world, and their culture is the linchpin of human history.” We are born into an egotistical society, where we view others as less than us. If someone has different opinions or values as we do, we tend to look down on them. This is similar to the concept of superiority when it comes to gender. Simone de Beauvoir wrote in Women as Other, “we should regard women’s nature as suffering from natural defectiveness”. This demonstrates how men are considered to be the superior gender and females are looked down on. 
	Growing up, we are drilled with social norms that we are expected to follow and live by. The idea of superiority is making the widening the gap between various groups of people and cultures. In the end, we are all humans. We need to differentiate between what is true and what society has been telling us to believe.

The Conception of Self
	With all the different influences of the world and people telling you to just be yourself, it is hard to figure out who that true self is. We all have a true self but depending on what social setting we are in determines which part of ourselves is shown. The conception of self has been molded by the different collective consciousnesses we are a part of. James and Mead both discuss the numerous perceptions of self we have. The collective consciousness gives us a false sense of self because we define ourselves by the society, we are a part of.
In The self and its selves, James divides the self into three parts; 1: its constituents- material, social, spiritual and self-preservation, 2: self-feelings, 3: self-seeking and preservation. The social self is a big part of we because it can have numerous parts, such as, family, friends, co-workers, church, school, etc. We put on a different persona when we are in each of these different groups of people. This is because as humans we have a greater range of emotions. Our greater range of emotions increases our fear of not being liked and of what others think of us. Mead relates to James’ conception of self by saying we are mainly our social selves. Our personality is shaped by those we surround ourselves with. People may have trouble discovering their true selves because they feel like they have multiple selves. 
Humans were not all born exactly the same and then shaped by society, but the people we are around do have a big part in shaping who we become. When humans started becoming social beings, they started to care more about how others perceived them. The collective consciousness we are a part of plays a big role in our personalities because we all want to feel like we belong, so we mold ourselves to the people we surround ourselves with. So, if the collective consciousness didn’t exist, who would we really be?

Essay Brief 7
Capitalism is abundant in our lives and is a driving force in America to this day. Karl Marx and Max Webber both go into depth on the framework of capitalism existing within our society and how it has been developing overtime. Estranged Labor and The Spirit of Capitalism and the Iron Cage emphasizes the idea that capitalism within societies contribute to inhibiting individuals from pursuing their dreams and passions. 
In the Spirit of Capitalism and the Iron Cage, Webber uses the concept of the iron cage to refer to how individuals tend to devote their lives to making money. If they do not live up their standards and the standards of society that our collective consciousnesses have formed overtime, then they have failed. Karl Marx goes into detail about the concept of alienation in his writing Estranged Labor. Marx believed that in the capitalistic society, the workers are exploited. Workers are treated as though their labor is property and can be sold or bought. Both of these authors point towards that capitalism puts shields on individuals eyes and leads them to making life changing decisions based on the money rather than what they truly want to do. 
I have seen capitalism and the concepts mentioned by Webber and Marx all throughout my life but have looked right past it for the longest time. I remember these ideas being evident is in my brother’s life recently. Shortly after getting out of college, my brother was offered two jobs; one was a job that he was super interested in but did not pay the most and the other was not very captivating but paid very well. My brother chose the second option and is in a spot now where he is blinded from the concepts within capitalism that are exploiting him. His collective consciousness and society have thrown these concepts at him and causing him to miss out on other opportunities. He is surrounded by people telling him to take the higher paying job, when they should be encouraging him to pursue his dreams and aim for what he loves. 
Capitalism is going to continue to exploit us as individuals and workers. Many people do not realize what capitalism to doing to our society. Americans need to wake up and realize that society has dictated so much of our life and we are allowing it to continue to do so. Society should not prevent us from doing what we love, it should push us to pursue our dreams. Our passions should be what drive us, not our money.

The Concept of Self
“One’s self concept is a collection of one’s beliefs about themselves” (Wikipedia). I am going to discuss where the self-concept comes from and how it is formed. Numerous scholars as discussed in class have different opinions on this. The concept of self is an important topic to discuss because how we define ourselves can affect self-esteem, increase social comparison and affect body-image.
The first study I want to discuss is Self-Concept and Self-Esteem: How the Content of the Self-Concept Reveals Sources and Functions of Self-Esteem. In this article, the authors discuss the four domains of self-image, “competence, morality, social acceptance and energetic dispositions”, (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg. 24).  A study was conducted to find out which of these domains had the most effect on self-esteem. The results found that self-evaluation involving acceptance of others was a clear predictor of self-esteem more than the other domains of self-concept (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg. 24). Susan Harter researched the correlation between Self-Concept and level of Self-Esteem and human development (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg.26). She found that kids who were more successful in sports, school, social status, etc. had higher self-esteem (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg.26). This can correlate to James’s concept of self, he believed we are mainly our social selves. The authors give credit to James for the development of self-concept. “The direct relation of the self-concept and self-esteem was postulated over one hundred years ago by William James (1980/1952) who stated that self-esteem is a product of an individual’s own sense of their achievements and aspirations,” (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg.25). The article goes on to talk about further research after James done by Jennifer Crocker with her model of contingencies of self-worth. According to Crocker, “The subjects of their research most frequently indicated appearance, others approval, outdoing others in competition, academic competency, love and support from family, virtue and God’s love,” (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg.25). Crockers research further makes James’s point that self-concept is greatly impacted by the social self. The authors also discuss Mead and Cooley, other scholars we discussed in class who believed, “social functioning and self-concept are directly connected”, “ Thus an individual’s self-concept and self-concept and self-esteem reflect how they are perceived and evaluated by others,” (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna ,Śniecińska, pg.25). These facts discovered by researchers show a great correlation between self-concept and self-esteem. We define our self-concept by other people which can put a lot of pressure on our social status and can affect our self-esteem. The authors go on to explain how higher self-esteem can give you a sense of belonging. Although, increasing self-esteem is difficult because, “According to the sociometer theory, proposed by Leary and his colleagues, self-esteem reflects the degree of acceptance by a group,” (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg.25) If you don’t feel accepted by a group this could lead to lower self-esteem, which can lead to greater risk for anxiety and depression which is a prominent issue in our current society. “Watson and colleagues (Watson et al., 2002) observed high correlations between self-esteem and positive and negative affectivity as well as between self-esteem and depression and anxiety,” (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg.25). So those with a lower self-esteem may have more of a risk for anxiety and depression. Another point James made was all the different social situations we find ourselves in, school, friends, church, work, family, etc. Feeling like you have to be a different person in each of these situations can put a lot of stress on a person, also increasing the chances of anxiety and depression. From the first person that defined self-concept, James, and these recent authors, the way we develop our self-concept tends to come mostly from other people, which is not good for our self-esteem. “This idea of self-esteem is consistent with the conclusions drawn by Baumeister and associates (2003) that self-esteem determines, among other things - initiation of activity, readiness to take up challenges, and perseverance in task executions,” (Kinga, Lachowicz-Tabaczek, Justyna, Śniecińska, pg.26). As you can see from these quotes self-esteem can have positive effects, but we need to change how we define our self-concept because that leads to low self-esteem. 
In the article, Relationships between the frequency of social comparisons and self-concept clarity, intolerance of uncertainty, anxiety, and depression, the authors discuss factors such as anxiety and depression. This study found correlation between anxiety and depression and social comparison. Social comparison can greatly affect our development of self-concept. Those who feel like they have more control of a defined self-concept tend not to compare themselves to others as much as those who have lower self-esteem (Butzer, Kuiper). Social comparison can turn into a downward spiral of negative thought about yourself. When we look to others to define our self-concept then it is hard for us to have a clear sense of who we are. The looking glass self was an idea that we discussed in class, formed by Cooley.  The looking glass self consists of three parts, “the imagination of our appearance to the other person, the imagination of our appearance to the other person, the imagination of judgement and pride or modification”, (Cooley).  The more an individual adheres to social comparison the more they will see themselves as the looking glass self. Comparison with others leads to wanting more and more that others have and wanting to be more like those around you. Constantly having to conform yourself to the world is exhausting and leads to dissatisfaction. Especially in current times it is much easier to compare yourself to others when we are surrounded with numerous social media platforms that constantly have people’s lives in your face. Most people post on social media when they are at their best not their worst. This idea was also discussed by Goffmon’s Presentation of Self.  He draws upon ‘the stage’ as an analogy of the presentation of self. In his analogy the front state is how you act in front of important people such as a professor or someone interviewing you for a job. The back-stage-self is who you are when you are around those you are most comfortable with (Goffman). Posting on social media could be an example of your front-stage-self. Therefore, comparing yourself to others on social media gives you a false sense of who others really are and gives you a false sense of who you are because people compare themselves to people performing on front stage.
Lastly, I want to discuss how misinterpretation of self-concept can lead to a negative body image.  Vartanian makes a great point of, “Without a clearly defined sense of self, individuals might seek external sources to provide coherence to identity,” (Vartanian, pg. 94). He discusses the issues that come up when the body defines the self, especially in women. As I discussed previously the media has a huge impact on how we perceive ourselves because we think we are supposed to conform ourselves to the perfect model image we see. This concept can be defined as the Beauty Myth, which is that women’s “worth” is in how they look (Wolf). Vartanian discusses this, but specifically regarding body image. He conducted a study that resulted in “lower self-concept clarity predicted a greater degree of internalization of social standards for women, but not for men,” (Vartanian, pg.94).  This article relates to Mead’s, The Self the I and the Me. He discusses how an experience of the body and an experience of self are two separate experiences. The body is just a vessel for the and the self is, “a reflection of the whole social process,” (Mead).  The body can do many things on its own without incorporating the self. There comes a risk when the self becomes a reflection of the body. Everyone is made different and there are some things you cannot change about your body. So, measuring your worth by your appearance or shape of your body can lead to many unhealthy habits. According to Vartanian, “Internalization of societal standards of attractiveness play a major role in the development of body image issues and disordered eating,” (Vartanian, pg.95). Those who have a lower clarity of self-concept are more likely to fall into these negative patterns of internalization of unrealistic social standards of attractiveness.  Vartanian goes on to explain a study which tested different characteristics that make people more likely to have a lower self-concept clarity. He found that factors that contribute to social-standard interiorization and self-concept clarity are conformity, public self-consciousness and body weight contingency (Vartanian, pg.117). This means that, “low self-concept clarity might lead to a general tendency to conform and a tendency to base one’s self-worth of of one’s body weight, which in turn lead individuals to adopt social standards of attractiveness as personally relevant beliefs, values or goal,” (Vartanian, pg.117). Conformity to these standards could lead to eating disorders such as Bulimia, “the strongest predictor for Bulimic behaviors was body image and dieting concerns for both men and women,” (Vartanian, pg.117). As you can see from this study low self-concept clarity can lead to an unhealthy view of yourself based on unrealistic standards from society, which in turn can lead to negative body-image and life-threatening eating disorders. This is a big factor into why our society needs to dismantle self-concept being based on others and find healthier ways to create a positive self-image. 
This idea of self-concept was defined long ago by James, but it's uncertainty and prominence in our society today is creating an unhealthy environment for many people surrounding mental health and body image. We must evaluate where self-concept comes from and how to find a clear self-concept. Some ways to do this include promoting positive body-image, reducing the help-seeking stigma around mental illness, reducing social-media use and endorsing positive feed and developing ways to increase self-esteem. These are a variety of ideas, but I believe they would effectively help society define self-concept more clearly, in turn increasing self-esteem so that it's less likely that they will fall into social comparison. It may take further research to implement these ideas and changes that need to be made in many different areas including, a more positive media, school systems and parents teaching and raising children to have a clear and positive concept of self. I believe this would decrease the percent of people who suffer with low self-esteem, decrease mental illnesses and eating disorders.
In conclusion, implementing ways to more clearly define self-concept may not be the only solution to decreasing low self-esteem, social comparison, and negative body-image in our society. Although, I believe finding clarity in who you are from an internal source rather than an external source can make an individual more confident in who they are and more successful in life.

Be a Man:
Hegemonic Masculinity and Commodity Fetishism in Media
Patriarchal masculinity is the belief that power is derived from violence and men hold the indisputable right to power. Therefore, it is only natural for media to reflect this attitude in movies, TV shows, video games, and more. However, showcasing the patriarchal standard of power in media has created a form of commodity fetishism that has directly linked itself to hegemonic masculinity. 
Commodity fetishism, coined by Karl Marx, in simple terms, refers to the overconsumption of goods and services. Although it also suggests more, it showcases a sense of superiority and an ignorance of how these goods and services come to be in the mind of the consumer. In relation to media, commodity fetishism reflects the ever-growing sources of entertainment that seek to satisfy the public’s gluttony. With the forming of new streaming platforms, the death of cable, and an infinite but also finite choice of selection. However, media cannot simply entertain; it is inevitable that it must also send a message to viewers. Due to patriarchal pressures, media oftentimes represents the desires of men both seeking and in power. As such, the creation of films like John Wick, Nobody, The Beekeeper, Taxi Driver, and many more serve the purpose of feeding a white male audience blood and guts through a screen. All of these films share a similar, if not the same, plot: a white male character, at first glance, lives an everyday life but is later revealed to be a deadly foe to those who have wronged him. As stated before, power has always been promised to men, not as something they should seek to gain, but as a right. With this in mind, it becomes apparent that the target audience of these films are white males who feel suppressed by their surroundings and wish to escape through violent means. The men showcased in these films are rage-filled. 
In Nobody, the main character begins off as a meek, quiet husband who appears to be jealous of his much more successful wife. And when he takes his wrath out on people he deems morally corrupt, he becomes addicted to the violence. On the surface, this plot is insignificant and could potentially provide a fruitful discourse. However, problems arise as the film continues and displays the main character’s acts of violence as fun and exhilarating. Another commonality of these films is the lack of female characters. Not only do these movies have very few female characters, but the ones that appear have no personality and exist solely to further the plot. The most obvious example of this is seen in the first John Wick movie, where the beginning plot point is the death of John’s wife, Helen. Despite Helen’s supposed importance to the plot, she is rarely named and is given no characterization apart from her relation to John. The two examples highlighted represent a significant problem in this genre of movies: either women are underrepresented, or they are made out to be threats to masculinity. Unfortunately, as seen with the numerous other media creations, gluttonous viewers will never be satisfied. So, an endless cycle of repetitive media will continue to feed the delusions of power-hungry men. 
However, men are not born bloodthirsty; instead, these standards are thrusted upon them with the use of hegemonic masculinity. In essence, hegemonic masculinity is patriarchy manifested. Analyzation of Harari’s Agreement with Class Material

21 Lessons for the 21st Century is an insightful book written by Israeli author Yuval Noah Harari. It addresses the political, technological, scientific, and sociological problems of today, as well as how humanity should face them in the coming future. According to Harari, we have no idea how the world will look in the year 2050. Harari offers priceless advice, perception, humor, and rationale in his quest to navigate the challenges of the twenty-first century In doing so, his goal is to provide some historian-based perspective so we as a people can begin trying to form some semblance of understanding going forward. The balance between introductory concepts and more abstract notions was carefully written and made for a thought-provoking read. However, since Harari comes from a more modern time, some of his ideals do not coincide with previously learned concepts, many of which were conjured hundreds of years ago. Still, as many sociological and philosophical concepts are for the most part unchangingly universally accepted, most of Harari’s writing agrees with theories learned in previous lessons. This essay seeks to examine how sociological concepts align with the insights of Harari. 
Most of the lessons we have learned in class were confirmed by Harari’s writing. The following is just one example, but arguably may be the strongest alignment. In module one, when the class was introduced to sociology, we reviewed Emile Durkheim and his perception of the significance of religion to human societies. According to Durkheim, “If religion has given birth to all that is essential in society, it is because the idea of society is the soul of religion” (p. 72). Here, Durkheim credits religion as the foundation of human civilization and society. He continues on by saying, “It is true that since collective sentiments can become conscious of themselves only by fixing themselves upon external objects; they have thus acquired a sort of physical nature; in this way they have come to mix themselves with the life of the material world…” (p. 72). When humans apply spiritual meaning to work, it becomes tangible. Durkheim names religion as the cause for objects in the material world, which constitutes human society.
To add onto Durkheim’s theory, in module one, the class explored The Neurology of Religion by Alexandra Maryanski and Jonathan Turner. The authors concluded that meaningful, abstract thought (for example, religious behavior and collective representations) can be explained by Darwinian natural selection. Hominin neuroanatomy evolved, making humans more social and able to form stable groupings. The adaptation of the brain of the ape Morotopithecus makes forming stronger social ties much more effective. “Humans are very disposed to give emotional significance to special situations, including their emotionally charged social relations” (Maryanski & Turner, 135). The authors connect the experience of emotion to social bonding, which is extremely important among humans for development in several different aspects (for example, cognitive, social, emotional, verbal, etc.). 
While Harari does not delve into the neurological and evolutionary aspects of society like Maryanski and Turner do, he instead stresses the importance of emotional and social bonding with others several times in the book. “In order to flourish we still need to ground ourselves in intimate communities” (p. 86). “...humans are social animals, therefore their happiness depends to a very large extent on their relations with others. Without love, friendship and community, who could be happy? If you live a lonely self-centred life, you are almost guaranteed to be miserable” (p. 206). He argues that social relationships are one of the most significant aspects of human health and wellbeing. Therefore, healthy and strong communities or societies cannot be formed without intimate connections between its members.
	Furthermore, the importance of religion in social bonding is emphasized in 21 Lessons for the 21st Century. Harari states that “Homo sapiens is a post-truth species, whose power depends on creating and believing fictions. Ever since the Stone Age, self-reinforcing myths have served to unite human collectives… By bringing people together, religious creeds make large-scale human cooperation possible. They inspire people to build hospitals, schools and bridges in addition to armies and prisons” (p. 240-241). He goes on further to argue that religion is the most effective tool in bringing humans together over a shared passion. It is successful in forming strong social ties with humans. So, not only are social bonds extremely important to humans for successful societies, but they may as well have not even been possible if not for religion as a shared passion. It is religion in some form or another that brings humans together, regardless of the connection they previously had. Religion is the universal connector, because of the importance of assigning meaning to phenomena. 
	Thus, Harari and Maryanski and Turner stress the importance of religion and social bonding when it concerns human civilization development. According to Maryanski and Turner, the evolution of the brain led to the inherent human ability to attribute emotional significance (usually with a religious subcontext) with a natural phenomena (usually rationally unexplainable by humans). This emotional significance transfers to meaningful relationships with human communities. Durkheim’s theory of religion being the foundation to society is only further proved by Maryanski and Turner’s research. In addition to this, Harari states that religion is extremely effective in strengthening cooperation and unity. With religion as a common uniter, humans can deepen their social and relational bonds, resulting in stronger communities and healthier individuals. 
While many of Harari’s ideas are in harmony with the theories and concepts explored in class, there is definitely a major conflicting idea regarding the philosophy of the self. In module two, we explored “The Self and Its Selves” by William James. James describes the “self” by dividing it into separate components. The material self is all that an individual possesses, whether it be their body, their money, their friends and family, or their reputation. The social self is the perception of the individual as seen by others. The spiritual self consists of one’s emotions and drives. Most importantly, the pure ego is the unchanging soul of the individual, which is stable regardless of one’s environment or experiences: “The sense of personal identity is not, then, this mere synthetic form essential to all thought. It is the sense of a sameness perceived by thought and predicated of things thought-about. These things are a present self and a self of yesterday…” (James, 1890). In this quote, James argues that the pure ego is true and consistent, unchanged by thoughts, perceptions of experiences, or emotions. He simplifies the different versions of the self by synthesizing one’s essence into a single, unmalleable soul. 
However, Harari contradicts James’s rationale in Chapter 21, Meditation. He reflects on what it means to live and be after explaining how the practice of meditation simplified his mental state to the here and now. Harari explains how it is human nature to become fascinated by the mystery of life after death and what that means to us as conscious beings. Many believe that “‘...the soul endures from birth to death and thereby holds life together…’”, but Harari argues that you cannot “observe a soul”, and the soul cannot be constant, because there is nothing that “endures from birth to death”. “The body keeps changing every moment, the brain keeps changing every moment, the mind keeps changing every moment” (p. 318). In this argument, Harari interconnects the mind and the soul- claiming that since the mind is perpetually changing in some form or another, the soul cannot possibly be a constant. 
Therefore, according to Harari, if the human mind is constantly adapting to new experiences and information, there is no possibility that the soul can be constant. The soul may not even exist because it is not observable, and we should not view the mind and soul as separate because they are too connected to ignore. Harari focuses on the perception of life and how physical sensations affect human bodies, not the abstract meaning of the self and one’s cosmic purpose. He pays strict attention to the observable, immediate senses. Since this is the only truly empirical evidence of human existence, it should be prioritized over the abstract pondering of eternal life and spirituality. Meanwhile, James attributes the human personality with an inherently permanent personal essence. It is untouched by experience or environmental input. The soul remains the same, even beyond physical death. James and Harari clearly disagree on the philosophical approach of human life and spirituality, especially when it concerns death. 
When reflecting on Harari’s perception of human sociology and the “lessons” he insightfully posits in 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, it can be confidently said that most of Harari’s ideas are consistent with the learned class material thus far. To recapitulate, Harari’s argument about the significance of religion and its social bonding power completely coincides with the research and theories of Maryanski, Turner, and Durkheim. Each of the three authors’s research or opinions perfectly complement each other. However, Harari’s opinion on what takes place after death does not agree with the theory of William James, who postulated that the pure ego is the ever-present and unchanging soul of a human being that transcends time and physical presence on Earth. It must be taken into consideration that James’s theory is considerably older, and Harari’s opinion stems from a personal experience (which he reflects on in Chapter 21, Meditation). Though, this disagreement is one of the few inconsistencies between opinions and is the most noticeably major. Reading 21 Lessons for the 21st Century successfully proves how sociological theories can approve or disprove each other, and is a powerfully stimulating opportunity to compare and contrast some of the most influential thinkers of human society.

How the Beauty Myth Affects Women in The Workplace
In 2016, I began my journey as a working woman in the United States by taking my first job as a cashier at Kentucky Fried Chicken. At that time, I was a sixteen-year-old, blonde haired, blue eyed, white girl and had never thought anything significant about my appearance. That was until my first day on the job. My manager assigned me to the front cashier position immediately rather than the back of the store. I was confused and inquired about his decision to put a first-time cashier front and center with the customer, not really knowing what I was doing at the time. He simply replied that “I appeared much more approachable than my other coworkers.” Therefore, in my manager’s opinion, it was more important to have someone to greet the customers that was more in line with societal beauty standards, than it was to have someone that was more qualified. Unfortunately, my story is not unique. Many women in all levels of the workforce have had similar experiences in their careers.
In 1991, author Naomi Wolf wrote about a concept that she called “the beauty myth”. As described by Wolf, the beauty myth is the unrealistic beauty standards society demands of women to achieve if they want to be accepted by society. In her writing, Wolf claims that this unrealistic beauty standard was created and enforced by men and exacerbated by the media and the marketplace. Furthermore, Wolf argues that the beauty myth was created to silently and indirectly keep women oppressed in society. In the 21st century, however, there are more women entering the workforce than ever before. The oppression created by the beauty myth is now translating to gender inequality in the workplace.  While gender is a protected class under United States law, the beauty myth creates a barrier for women in the workforce because these unrealistic beauty standards make it more difficult for women to be hired and promoted into well paid careers.  These unrealistic beauty standards can be argued as being an even bigger obstacle than racial bias for women of color in the workforce as personal appearance is not a protected class under current United States law.
First, the beauty myth creates a barrier for woman in the workforce because these unrealistic beauty standards make it more difficult for women to be hired and promoted as has been proven in scientific studies. Of these studies, one conducted by Leeat Ramati-Ziber and Nurit Shnabel of Tel-Aviv University and Peter Glick of Lawrence University, aimed to investigate whether such beauty standards make it more difficult for women to be hired and move up into higher-level career positions.  
Another scientific study conducted by Ramati-Ziber, Shnabel, and Glick, examined appearance-related discrimination towards women who seek out higher positions within a workplace context. The study provided evidence that there are more appearance standards imposed on women in the workplace than those placed on men. Women who seek out higher positions are more likely to be required to strive to these levels and maintain an attractive appearance far greater than those placed on men. The study included a sample of 206 undergraduate students at an Israeli University. Of the participants, 93 were women and 113 were men.  Their ages ranged from 22 to 39 years of age. The study was initiated by measuring the sexism of each individual participant using a questionnaire. The questionnaire asked participants to assign either a female employee or male employee to a list of 12 different occupations.   These occupations included low-power and high-power positions.  The jobs also fell within six masculine domains. The participants were then asked to indicate the amount of money and time an employee working in each occupation should invest in his or her appearance for each month as part of their professional duties.
This study found that participants in this survey demanded a much higher appearance-related investment from female employees in high-power positions as opposed to men in the same positions.  Thus, making it harder for women to receive promotions within the same job classifications as men due to these added beauty requirements. “In other words, sexists made especially strong, discriminatory beauty-investment demands toward precisely those women who most directly threaten gender hierarchy.  That is, women who were in more powerful, masculine occupations.” (Ramati-Ziber et al., 2019). This quote explains the findings of this study and relates to “the beauty myth”.   Wolf stated, “Recent research consistently shows that inside the majority of the West's controlled, attractive, successful working women, there is a secret "underlife" poisoning our freedom; infused with notions of beauty, it is a dark vein of self-hatred, physical obsessions, terror of aging, and dread of lost control.” (Wolf 1). The “secret underlife” poisoning women that Wolf is referring to is the pressure of discriminatory beauty-investment that is placed on women in the workplace and is proved by the above study.
The next study we need to look at was conducted by Ramati-Ziber, Shnabel, and Glick, which examined if individuals with job interview experience would impose a higher beauty standard tax on women who were interviewing for high and low-level positions. This study looked at a sample of 55 men and 45 women with a mean age of 45 years old, all with experience in conducting interviews within the hiring process. The participants were asked to give their professional impression of a candidate after they were shown a picture of a female candidate and determine in their opinions, the level of position for which the  candidate should apply. The only differences between the pictures of the candidates were the presence of or lack of fingernail polish as well as straight or non-straight hair. The study found that these hiring-level employees that do in fact hire outside candidates, penalized women for not meeting beauty standards.   Even though these hiring managers had large amounts of experience in interviewing candidates, they possessed negative attitudes towards women perceived as not meeting these beauty standards and especially towards women who were applying for the more powerful positions. 
The findings of this study relate to the “The Beauty Myth” when Wolf said “It is no accident that so many potentially powerful women feel this way. We are in the midst of a violent backlash against feminism that uses images of female beauty as a political weapon against women's advancement: the beauty myth.” (Wolf 1). The findings of the study relate to this quote from “The Beauty Myth” because the results of the study prove Wolf’s statement to be correct. The findings of the study prove that female beauty is being used by people with job interviewing experience to prevent women from being hired into higher positions. 
Additionally, the beauty myth is shown to have such a profound influence on the way women are treated in the workforce that it is a bigger obstacle than racial bias is for women of color in the workforce. A study conducted by N. Michelle Hughes and Cedric Herring aimed to investigate if skin tone and the beauty myth affected the way African American women are treated in the workplace. 
The study examined a sample of 393 employed African American women. The study began by collecting demographic information and recording the physical characteristics, such as skin tone and hair texture of each participant. The study then asked all the participants to fill out a self-reported questionnaire aimed at determining if they ever felt “hassled at work” or been unfairly denied a promotion based on their appearance. 
The study found that although skin color does play a role in how African American are treated at work, the results found that shockingly, regardless of skin tone the more “attractive” the appearance of the women, the more likely they reported being hassled at work and denied promotions. “The results suggest that the more attractive a woman is judged to be, the more likely she is to report being hassled at work” (Hughes & Herring 177). This quote describing the results of this study truly shows how deeply rooted the beauty myth is in creating barriers for women. It is so deeply rooted that it even is, according to the study, a more deciding factor in female workplace treatment than racial bias. The result of this study further reinforces how important it is that the beauty myth be addressed and undermined to benefit women of all races and ethnicities. 
Now that it has been determined through research that the beauty myth is negatively impacting women in the workforce and creating barriers for female advancement, the question remains as to the best solution. It is a complicated question to answer. Under current United States law, gender is a protected group in employment, and it is illegal to discriminate against an individual based on gender. However, there is no law that protects an individual from being discriminated against based on their appearance. An excellent example of this is the restaurant Hooters. Hooters has had a very appearance-based discriminatory hiring practice since the inception of the company. For a woman to work as a waitress at hooters she is required to be deemed attractive with a thin body and large breasts. A woman who works at Hooters is required to wear specific makeup, painted fingernails, and have only “natural” colored hair. The hiring practices that Hooters utilizes, which are solely based in ideal beauty standards, should not be legal. 
To stop the beauty myth from continuing to undermine and oppress women in the workforce, appearance must become a protected group under US employment law. In her article “APPEARANCE MATTERS: A PROPOSAL TO PROHIBIT APPEARANCE DISCRIMINATION IN EMPLOYMENT”, author Elizabeth M. Adamitis emphasizes the role that beauty plays in our society and how beauty is considered as a legitimate consideration in employment matters. “Further, the focus on appearance serves to perpetuate and foster harmful societal inequities.” (Adamitis 195). This quote from Adamitis directly relates to the beauty myth because she is sharing the same opinion that Wolf expresses in her writing, that the focus on appearance in employment is to intentionally create workplace inequality between men and women. Furthermore, Adamitis writes, “Women are often both considered and expected to be more attractive than men.” (Adamitis 199). This quote is relating to both study five and three described above because the statement is consistent with the findings of both studies.
In conclusion, the beauty myth has created many inequalities for women in the workforce. The beauty myth affects all women and makes it harder for women to get hired or to advance to high power positions during their career. Although gender discrimination is against the law, appearance discrimination is not. This allows employers a way to discriminate against women without having to cite their gender as the reason. The best solution to fix this unequal treatment it to also make appearance a protected group under law.

Matrix of Domination and Intersectionality
	Will it ever be possible to fully understand and dismantle oppression in our world? It is necessary to understand terms such as intersectionality and the matrix of domination to attack this question. These ideas help break down what oppression and domination are and how they can be stopped. One must understand their own experiences with oppression and even their own experience with privilege before one can begin to contribute to the dismantling of oppression. 
	This would be a good time to describe my own experience with oppression, more specifically the lack thereof given my situation as a heterosexual, white, male. The privilege was prevalent, and subconscious throughout my childhood as I was oblivious to most kinds of oppression and what was going on in our world, outside of my own life. I came to this conclusion at a time I can only describe as an embarrassingly late age when I found out that Uncle Terry, my dad’s best friend from his childhood who is also black, wasn’t my uncle. Thinking back on the time I have spent with Uncle Terry; I recall a time when he told me about “the talk” that he had with his parents when he was younger. “The talk” was given to inform him and his siblings how to deal with the police if they ever were to encounter them. He described it as a very serious, hard, and sad talk to have with his parents. 
	Hearing this story was astounding for me at the time because I felt that I never really had a reason to fear the police. As I got a little older, learned more about current events and oppression in our world, I realized that racism was only one of the many levels of oppression in our society. 
This realization of mine was me grasping the idea of intersectionality. Intersectionality is a term that was coined by Kimberlé Crenshaw who was a pioneering writer on civil rights, critical race theory, and Black feminist legal theory. Crenshaw defined the term to describe how many individual characteristics intersect with one another and overlap. These individual characteristics include race, gender, sexuality, class, religion, and anything else that is used to define a person.  She defined and introduced this theory in 1989 with her paper “Demarginalizing the Intersection of Race and Sex: A Black Feminist Critique of Antidiscrimination Doctrine, Feminist Theory, and Antiracist Politics.” Crenshaw used intersectionality to convey that being black and being a woman is not independent of one another. Intersectionality has become more widely known over time and has become mainstream over the past ten years. 
I know that my Uncle Terry has been approached by police in his life, though I am not quite sure how it played out, his situation could be described using intersectionality. Not only was he black, but he is also a man which may be thought of by the police to be more of a threat than say a black woman or even a white man. Since intersectionality includes all aspects of one’s character, even height could be a factor. Terry is around 6’3”-6’4” which definitely would have played a role in that situation. Intersectionality also counts privileges on top of oppression. A privilege that I know Terry has is that he is highly educated which would also have influenced his situation. His position of oppression most likely outweighs his privilege in this scenario. 
People can be privileged and oppressed at the same time, just adding to the complexities of domination and oppression in our society. The Intersecting Axes of Privilege, Domination, and Oppression was adapted from Kathryn Pauly Morgan, “Describing the Emperor’s New Clothes: Three Myths of Educational (In)Equality.” The graph is made up of two sides, one listing the axes of privilege and the other listing the axes of oppression. For example, the axes include genderism, sexism or androcentrism, racism, eurocentrism, heterosexism, ableism, educationalism, ageism, politics of appearance, classicism, language bias, colorism, anti-Semitism, and pro-natalism. This graph does a great job breaking down the many levels of privilege and oppression without overlapping the social identities. 
Patricia Hill Collins was another person who played a major role in analyzing problems with oppression. She is a distinguished sociology professor at the University of Maryland, College Park. She integrated ideas of intersectionality and coined the phrase “matrix of domination” in her writing “Black Feminist Thought in the Matrix of Domination.” In her writing, she emphasizes how Afrocentric feminist thought “demonstrates Black women’s emerging power as agents of knowledge. By portraying African American women as self-defined, self-reliant individuals confronting race, gender, and class oppression.” 
Collins integrates intersectionality in her writing by portraying African American women as agents of knowledge. According to the idea of intersectionality, few people are entirely a victim or entirely an oppressor. Some individuals display privileges and oppression. Collins is emphasizing how African American women are one of the few people with so much oppression based on their identity. She also emphasizes how this position that African American women are in is necessary and must be used to produce Black feminist thought. This is very difficult to accomplish because it also requires an African American woman to overcome the widely known, Eurocentric ideologies. It is necessary because as much as white feminists point out their oppression as being a woman, they unintentionally refuse to see their privileges of being white. This reinforces the idea of the matrix of domination and intersectionality and how race and gender cannot be independent of one another. 
Through Collins’ analysis of the matrix of domination, she includes the multiple levels of domination. The three levels people experience oppression are the level of personal biography, the group or community level, and the systemic level of social institutions. 
The level of personal biography focuses on the unique experiences, unique identities, and the relationships that follow. A situation of domestic violence is an example of oppression on the level of personal biography. These situations tend to have multiple points of view for interpretation.  The level of personal biography is an example of how domination does not only occur through top-down processes. 
The level that is shared by a group or community is the next example of how domination experiences and how oppression is resisted. This is where the cultural context of domination is found as groups can be defined by race, religion, age, class, and gender. Collins often focuses on this level of domination to emphasize the Afrocentric feminist group’s perspective. 
The final level, and largest, is the systemic level in social institutions. This level includes all the examples of domination that occur in social institutions such as schools, churches, and the media. This is the level most people would think of when the topic of domination and oppression should arise. 
Collins concludes her paper, “Black Feminist Thought in the Matrix of Domination,” by emphasizing the importance of dialogue and empathy. There is, what seems to be, an infinite number of perspectives and standpoints. Collin’s includes a quote by Elsa Barkley Brown where she claims that eventually such dialogues may get us to a point at which “all people can learn to center in another experience, validate it, and judge it by its standards without need of comparison or need to adopt that framework as their own. [In such dialogues], one does not need to ‘decenter’ anyone to center someone else; one has only to constantly, appropriately, ‘pivot the center.’” This quote emphasizes that it is important to be able to share one’s own unique experiences. On top of this, it is important to listen to other unique perspectives, learn about them, and respond. 
Much progress has been made to dismantle oppression in society and make way toward equality for all, but there is still much that needs to be done. Oppression, prejudice, racism, sexism, or anything that involves the domination of an individual or group, is so much more complex than it seems. Before we can attack these ideals and dismantle oppression, one must gain a better understanding of what oppression means and the many levels of domination and resistance. One can gain a better understanding through ideas and theories such as the matrix of domination and intersectionality. 
Even though the solution to this problem may be far in the future, it is still very possible. The best way to continue to make progress toward equality is through children and young adults. Adding more classes that go farther into the depths of oppression in our society. These classes would include ideas that Patricia Hill Collins and Kimberlé Crenshaw emphasize in their papers along with many other ideas and concepts against oppression. One must point out examples of oppression instead of trying to ignore or forget. It is also important to point out privileges one has because of their characteristics. Identifying examples of oppression and privileges in one’s own life is the beginning of dismantling oppression in society today.

Baptism by Fire: 
An in-depth look at the unique sub-culture of U.S. Military veterans from a sociological perspective
	Tattooed, with short-cropped hair and walking with a self-assured swagger, veterans are easily identifiable in contemporary society. Emphasizing honor, duty, and patriotism while also encouraging tattoos, aggressiveness, and foul language, veteran sub-culture can be as unique as it is vexing to those who’ve never experienced it first-hand. Unlike most other professions in modern society, military service molds for its adherents a new identity and culture that sticks with its individuals for life. Through training, deployments, combat, and camaraderie, veterans have developed similar values, beliefs, and sense of self identity in stark contrast to who they were before. Service in the United States Military, more so than any other culture or sub-culture, is able to forge a new and lifelong culture out of innumerable different individual identities and cultures.
	A few weeks ago in my introduction to Film Studies class, we watched a very avant-garde film which featured a live childbirth scene. This scene was graphic and didn’t hold anything back: a series of direct shots of a child being born, with very little editing done to conceal any of the viscera or vivid imagery that went along with such a process. Needless to say, this scene turned some stomachs amongst the students viewing it; so much so that one of my classmates vomited during the scene. In response to this, the film was stopped, and the lights were turned on to ensure the safety of the unfortunate student who had succumbed to the graphic images shown on screen. It was at this moment that I unknowingly and subconsciously reacted with an act that would be widely considered uncouth and inappropriate in most civilian circles: I cheered. 
Is this because I’m a sadist who enjoys seeing pain in others? Is it because my own pride is dependent upon seeing others fail where I succeed? Is it because I’m unable to read social situations appropriately and chose the wrong reaction to such an event? The answer is much more nuanced and involves many layers of enculturation.
Drawing on my own personal experience from the Marine Corps, there is a saying: pain is weakness leaving the body. This saying permeates throughout all aspects of life in the Marine Corps – be it physical training, sleep deprivation, or studying for tests. Consequently, when Marines see others enduring physical pain but pushing through, it is seen as the individual experiencing pain become stronger. There is no better example of this than the infamous “Indian run”. This particularly grueling exercise involves a group of around twelve Marines running in a single file line, with the Marine at the front of the line holding an ammunition can usually weighing around thirty pounds. While still running, the Marine at the front will pass the can to the Marine behind them, then to the Marine behind them, until it reaches the Marine at the back of the line. The last Marine will then sprint to the front, carrying the can the entire time, and start the process all over again. This process can last for miles, and many Marines end up vomiting from the physical strain. However, more often than not, the exhausted Marine will get back in line and continue the training. This process of overcoming physical pain and pushing through what was believed to be the absolute physical limit is often met with cheers and rallying cries from onlookers, because it is perceived to be the act of becoming stronger in real time.
So by cheering at my fellow student for getting sick at a film, was I being insensitive? Or, much more plausibly, was I enacting a response engrained in me by the culture of “shedding weakness through physical hardship”? Much like active military culture, veteran culture holds toughness, aggressiveness, and tenacity as sacred values. 
This focus on resilience and steadfastness plants deep roots within the souls of those served in the military, carrying over into the veteran culture. When in active military service, veterans witnessed the real-world necessity of these values played out, further deepening their importance in the minds of veterans. Veterans have witnessed first-hand the effects of great triumph of high achievement and the disastrous consequences of giving up, which are incredibly unifying ideals when uniting so many from a variety of different cultures and upbringings. These ideals cement themselves so concretely in the hearts of veterans that they leave an indelible mark on the psyche of the veteran even after leaving service. 
The French scholar Emile Durkheim observed that any given society develops what he called a “collective consciousness”. This consciousness is the amalgamation of what is to be highly regarded in a society and what is to be avoided – what is morally good and what is morally wrong. Furthermore, this consciousness, as Durkheim points out, is what unifies individuals into a society, merging individuals into a stream of relatively common thought. This unifying cohesion of what values ought to be held sacred can further manifest itself in collective representations, that is, tangible representations of intangible ideas. A cross, for example, may appear simply to be two bisecting lines, but believers may see it as a representation of the Christian faith. A crescent moon and star may seem to be two celestial bodies next to one another but may represent Islam and all of its pillars to others. These symbols are indeed representations of the collective consciousness, signifying what values and beliefs are desirable to the culture that holds them.
Collective representations of the collective consciousness of military culture are abundant and clearly encompass military values. Many symbols will often include skulls, rifles, predatory animals, and stars, representing lethality, weapon mastery, tenacity, and patriotism, respectively. These symbols often conjure up images of brutal wartime prowess, like the skull and southern cross of the Marine Raiders, or historical patriotism, like the screaming eagle of the 101st airborne division. These representations of the collective consciousness are often held as holy relics to the veterans who served in those units, manifesting itself on t-shirts, buttons, or tattoos. They are seen as icons, representing a long and proud history in which they played a role; a sacred tradition they got to be a part of. It is through these symbols of the collective military consciousness that veterans develop and maintain their unique culture, as despite their time in active service being over, it remains a part of who they are.
Veteran sub-culture can safely be described, therefore, as a continuation of military culture. A culture that breaks down the potential clash of ideals of so many individuals from so many different societies and philosophies and rebuilds them as a unified identity. Through the pain and hardship and subsequent victories and achievements of the rigorous military life, a collective consciousness is born among those who served in the United States military unlike any other in contemporary societies. Through symbols and representations depicting a warrior culture and bonds of brotherhood, veterans maintain their values of honor, toughness, aggressiveness, and tenacity into their civilian lives. As Emilie Durkheim pointed out, this collective consciousness solidifies the values and aspirations of veterans stronger than any other culture so far seen in modern society.
