The Sociological Subculture of the Modern Day Warfighter
	While much of military training is centered on physical fitness and tactical proficiency there is much more that goes into producing a capable warfighter.  You can take any person off the street, teach them how to hold a rifle and have them do push ups until they collapse but that won’t make them any more capable in battle.  The reason why the Marine Corps training pipeline is so effective in producing capable warriors from the everyday citizen is because along with the physical training it has instilled a completely separate collective consciousness among its members.  This is a process that begins in bootcamp and continues on until the day that a service member is discharged from active duty.  Throughout this paper I will discuss how the Marine Corps infantry training pipeline creates a subculture with its own collective consciousness and why it is necessary in order to facilitate combat effectiveness.
	The best way to show the sociological development of an infantryman is to follow the training pipeline in chronological order, starting with boot camp.  One of the most significant changes which takes place at this step is the removal of what Goffman refers to as the self in his writings.  From the moment a recruit steps off the bus they become an object.  The words I, me, my, he, us, they and them become “this recruit, that recruit, those recruits and these recruits.”  Referring to yourself or any other recruit as a person is met with swift punishment from the drill instructors.  Next all heads are shaved and everyone is put into the same uniform.  Once everyone is uniform, every single part of your life is now regimented, from the time you wake up in the morning down to what utensils you are allowed to eat with.  By removing all sources of individuality, the recruit becomes an object.  Their sense of self is no more.  This is necessary for breaking down civilian habits and creating a blank canvas to resculpt the recruit into a warrior which values the needs of the organization above their own wants and needs.  Another key part in shaping a Marine is the language which is permitted.  For example as I mentioned before a recruit is not allowed to refer to themselves or any other recruit as a person but there are also many other forms of prescribed language which is used to mentally condition the recruit for aggression.  For one, a recruit is never allowed to speak in a voice any lower than yelling as loud as they can.  The word “kill” is used as a response and chanted before recruits complete mundane tasks such as washing their hands before eating and curse words as well as insults are hurled at the recruits non stop by the drill instructors.  Other phrases such as “slay bodies”, “kill bodies”  and “stack bodies” are widely used by Marines for the same purpose.  Overall the purpose of bootcamp is to create the most stressful environment possible to acclimate recruits to and to remove their individuality in order to create a Marine who values his peers wants and needs as well as the organization’s needs over his or her own (Novaco 1991).
	Now that the individual has been broken down and had their civilian collective consciousness replaced the formation of the Marine Corps collective consciousness can begin.  While this replacement does begin in bootcamp, for the infantryman it really begins to take root in the school of infantry, which is where infantry Marines receive their infantry specialty such as machine gunner, rifleman, mortarman etc.  While these hard skills were the main objective of training there were many soft skills and mental conditioning methods which were implemented on the side.  One of these being furthering our desensitization and conditioning to violence.  In order to achieve this combat instructors would often recount their war stories and during our classes we would be shown graphic videos of executions, death and gore to normalize it.  I found this aspect of the training interesting because it was something that happened on the side with little to know extra thought but the changes it made in our heads was substantial.  Marines began to be entertained by these videos and at times would seek them out on their own accord.  Weapons training and desensitization aside, what I found to be the most important aspect of SOI (school of infantry)  was the camaraderie and trust it formed between us.  This is perhaps the most vital trait of an infantry Marine and is imperative to war fighting because cohesion is essential for unit performance as well as overcoming stressors.  You can ask any war vet and they will tell you that they put the Marines to the left and the right of them above themselves, and going into war knowing that is extremely reassuring.  The amount of trust gained in military training has been tested across multiple military occupations and in the end it was found that infantry training yielded the highest levels of cohesion(Orme 2020).  This is no surprise when considering the substandard living conditions which trainees go through together.  To name just a few events which brought my platoon closer to each other was a field operation in which we were awake to the point of visual and auditory hallucination and a 13 mile hike with over 150lbs. of gear on us in gale force winds.  There is something about “embracing the suck” with fellow Marines which creates bonds which are often as close as family. 
	Once a Marine has completed their infantry training and has gained their respective military occupation specialty they are shipped off to their unit.  The general principles of being a Marine such as discipline and putting the organization first should be set in stone by this point.  The unit or “the fleet” as it is called is a place where skills are refined and the Marine fully settles into their new ways.  The platoon they belong to becomes their new family and in some cases even more than family.  The fleet is also where you begin to have more exposure to the Marine Corps traditions including some of the less traditional ones such as hazing.  One widely known tradition among infantrymen is “pinning and bloodstriping.”  Pinning takes place when a Marine reaches the rank of Lance Corporal and it is when the newly promoted Marine wears their new rank without pin backings for 24 hours.  For those 24 hours any Marine who is a Lance Corporal or above punches and jams the pins into the Marines chest.  Blood stripping is when a Marine reaches the rank of Corporal and becomes a non commissioned officer.  It is the same principle as pinning but instead of stabbing a Marine with pins they knee the side of the new NCO’s legs until they can no longer walk.  To the average collective consciousness this would be seen as undesirable and something to be avoided, but for Marines this is a cherished tradition which has been passed down through generations of infantry Marines.  There is also the tradition of celebrating the Marine Corps birthday every year which is a sacred event among Marines, more so than any other holiday.  Another key part of the average Marines collective consciousness is the elevation of Marines such as Chesty Puller and John Basilone as gods.  John Basilone is literally the God of machine gunnery to Marines and Chesty Puller is a larger than life, undying, killing machine who is used as the pinnacle of leadership.  Another tradition which is noteworthy, is the structure of rank.  While superior ranks are to be fully respected and obeyed to a level beyond any example in the civilian world, senior Marines are also held to the standard that they must treat their juniors better than they would treat themselves.  This does not mean that you must be kind and never yell at your juniors but for example when I was a section leader, we would never let our junior Marines see us sleep or eat, meaning that you don't eat until all of your guys are fed, you don’t sleep until all of them are sleeping, and you wake up before any of them wake up.  This is important to take note of because as we discussed in class a collective consciousness is formed anytime humans interact in some pattern over time and many of the aspects which form the Marine Corps’ collective consciousness oppose what would be considered the status quo in the civilian population.  In summary the fleet is where you become “a true killer”, it is where you learn the Marine Corps ethos of running towards the sound of gunfire, and caring for the life of your fellow Marine more than your own life.  
There is a reason the Marine Corps is called a cult.  We raise our idols to god hood, we have many traditions and methods which seem extreme, and our mentality seems a bit frightening, but these are all social and mental adaptations of a collective consciousness belonging to a culture whose job is to fight and often die on the orders handed down to them.  This is why coming back to normal life after being completely reprogramed is an incredibly difficult task for most Marines whether they experienced combat or not (Doruk, 2008).  They have essentially left behind their original collective consciousness and had a new one shoved into them only to have to transition back on their own once they re-enter normal life.  However, that Marine Corps collective consciousness never truly leaves.  For myself, I struggled with adjustment disorder and culture shock upon re entering civilian life.  I still hold my morbid sense of humor which many of us adapt as a coping mechanism as well as a higher tolerance to stress.  All in all, the Marine Corps is unique among the American military because of the indoctrination into its own collective consciousness.  While this occurs in other branches to a degree, it is not comparable to the level which it does for the Marines.

Social Media and Its Influence on Body Image and Mental Health
	Social media is a new type of media that is entirely user generated. The most popular forms of social media are Facebook, Instagram, Twitter, and TikTok. As new forms of social media are created and gain popularity, along with technology advancements in smartphones, people have an increased level of accessibility to these platforms. What impact does this increased accessibility have on people, especially teenagers? How does it affect one’s sense of self, their body image, and their self-esteem? Social media can be beneficial, as it allows us to easily and quickly do things like connect with friends and family and stay updated with current news, but the effect it may have on one’s mental and physical health can be detrimental. 
	The concept of body image can be defined in a number of different ways. One of the main definitions is that body image is the way that a person sees their physical appearance, and the feelings and emotions that come from that perception, whether they be positive or negative (Jiosta). One’s body image reflects society’s social norms, thus pertaining to the concept of the collective consciousness. People will always strive to look their personal best, but the beauty norms of society often portray people who are tall, thin, tan and with clear skin as being the “ideal” model for what we should all look like. This can lead to things like tanning, buying expensive clothes, shoes and makeup, and working out and dieting excessively. Many people alter their appearance to fit into these high beauty standards. In a study done by Meier and Gray, it was found that an increased exposure to social media can be connected to “weight dissatisfaction, a drive for thinness, thin ideal internalization, and self-objectification among female high school students”. 
Traditional media, like newspaper and magazines, has had a negative impact on people’s body image for decades, according to Fardouly and Vartanian. Social media is different from traditional media as it allows users to display themselves, rather than just seeing celebrities and models. People put forth their best self on social media. Not many people want to broadcast the “undesirable” aspects of their lives on social media. Photos can be edited, filtered, and altered to make them seem more attractive. These images do not portray who you are normally, but rather show an enhanced version of yourself. This leads to an increase in body dissatisfaction, as people feel as though they can more closely relate to peers on social media rather than models and celebrities in traditional media.
	As new forms of social media arise, we begin to notice the major differences between social and traditional media: the use of likes and who runs each platform. Social media is peer and user generated, which traditional media is generated by major corporations and paparazzi. Social media focuses on interaction, while traditional media does not (Kim). Likes and comments are a form of instant gratification, which can lead to an obsession with this type of feedback. The amount of views, likes and comments on posts can lead to negative feelings about ourselves and our appearance. Comments are a quintessential part of social media, as they guide perceptions on what is deemed “ideal”. We strive for this instant gratification and modify our beauty standards to fit within the societal norm in order to receive more positive feedback from our peers.
	In an article written by Tiggemann and Anderberg, the trend of “Instagram versus Reality” is discussed as being a form of online social activism. This trend shows two side by side photos of the same person. In the first photo, the person is their ideal self, wearing nice clothes and makeup with their hair done. This photo is edited and taken from flattering angles. In the second photo, the person shoes their “natural” self, without makeup or filters, posed in a more natural and comfortable way. This trend is very important, as it allows people to realize that what is posted on social media is entirely different from who people are when no one is looking.  “Instagram versus Reality” serves as a way to remind people that what is posted on social media is often not the truth, but rather a lie and a coverup to make people seem more put together and “perfect” than they actually are, This exposure to “natural” photos leads to lower facial and body dissatisfaction, and an increase in body appreciation and positive body image. According to Tiggemann and Anderberg, positive body image is a multidimensional construct that refers to love, respect and acceptance of one’s body. People realize that their body is serving its purpose: keeping us alive. An increase in body appreciation can lead to greater self-esteem, self-care and adaptive eating. Once people begin to realize the truth behind social media, they will start to become more satisfied with their own bodies.
	The negative effects of social media have generally been connected to the process of social comparison (Tiggemann and Anderberg). People who are the targets for comparison on social media are usually peers, whereas in traditional media, the targets are models and celebrities. The comparison with peers often results in body dissatisfaction, as people who do the comparison see their peers to be “normal” people that they can relate to more closely than they could with models and celebrities.  This body dissatisfaction is often detrimental to one’s mental health and confidence in their appearance.
	Social media provides a very narrow view of one’s life. Not many people choose the broadcast the chaos and disorder of their everyday lives on social media. Erving Goffman proposes the idea that people are “performers”. In his writing, “Presentation of Self”, Goffman states that each person has a front and a backstage. The backstage is made up of actions that people do “behind the scenes”, when no one is looking. Think of the backstage as your true self, without filters. The front stage is made up of actions that others can see, or the character that you show your “audience”. The front and backstage theory can be applied to social media. The backstage is your true, everyday self, while the front stage is how you appear on social media platforms. This appearance that people put on display is often very different from who they actually are as a person.
	Social media can also be used as a platform for bullying. It is easy to make a fake account with none of your personal information and to use that account to bully others. Social media provides a “curtain” for bullies to become anonymous. It is much easier to say hateful things to others behind a screen than to their face. According to Peled, cyberbullying is defined as electronic posting of mean messages about a person, often done anonymously. Types of cyberbullying include fraping, dissing, trolling, catfishing, phishing, stalking, blackmail, the sharing of photos and videos that one wants to keep private, shunning, and sexting. Fraping occurs when someone makes a social media account pretending to be someone else, Dissing is done in an attempt to ruin someone else’s reputation. Trolling is trying to provoke a reaction from someone else. Catfishing involves stealing someone’s identity to create profiles used to deceive someone. Phishing is a tactic used to trick or manipulate someone into revealing personal information, like bank account numbers, addresses, and social security numbers. Blackmail is a threat to reveal someone’s secrets. Many of these bullying tactics would never be done face to face with the victim, so social media provides a perfect platform for these types of bullying. Cyberbullying can lead to mental health disorders like anxiety and depression and may also cause body dysmorphia and eating disorders. Victims of cyberbullying may also become lonely, have low self-esteem, gain phobias of school, and show poor performance in school or at work. 
	Social media will forever change the way people interact with one another. What was once face to face interactions is now done online. This causes people to put forth a version of themselves that is entirely different from who they are. Real life shows the raw, natural, and unedited version of who you are, whereas social media allows you to filter how you are seen to others. The use of social media is a great way to stay updated with current events and to connect with people around the world, but it also provides the perfect platform for anonymous bullying. Social media can also have a negative impact on one’s self-esteem, their body image, and their mental health. As we use more and more forms of social media, we need to remind ourselves that what we see on these platforms often is not one’s true self. We are able to select the best version of ourselves to put forth, rather than putting forth who we truly are. We need to stop comparing our physical appearance to that of others. Once we realize that each and every person has an appearance and personality that is unique and perfect, we will be able to build a more positive and accepting environment.
